          Programming note: Money Stuff will be off tomorrow and Monday, ba=
ck on Tuesday.

 =20
   =20
      TMTG / DWAC
   =20
 =20

Digital World Acquisition Corp. is a special-purpose acquisition company th=
at has   signed a deal to merge with Trump Media & Technology Group Corp., =
which runs Donald Trump=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9CTruth Social=E2=80=9D network,=
=C2=A0and take it public.=C2=A0Like most SPACs, DWAC has a time limit to co=
mplete its deal: Its corporate charter says that, if it has not completed a=
 merger by Sept. 8 =E2=80=94=C2=A0next Thursday =E2=80=94=C2=A0it has to cl=
ose up shop and return its money to shareholders. It is definitely not goin=
g to complete its=C2=A0merger with TMTG=C2=A0by next Thursday. (The main ho=
ldup is that the US Securities and Exchange Commission needs to review and =
sign off on the  proxy statement for that merger; the SEC has  various ques=
tions.) Actually DWAC can  extend that deadline by six months, if its spons=
ors put up some more money, but six months probably isn=E2=80=99t enough ei=
ther.=C2=A0So DWAC has  asked its shareholders for a longer extension: It h=
as asked them to vote to approve an amendment to its charter to extend the =
deadline by a year to Sept. 8, 2023.
  [1]
 The vote will be held at an online special meeting of shareholders next Tu=
esday, Sept. 6, two days before the current deadline.
If you are a DWAC shareholder, how should you vote on this proposal? There =
is really only one conceivable answer. Whether or not you like Donald Trump=
, TMTG, Truth Social, etc.,
  [2]
=C2=A0the simple fact is that DWAC=E2=80=99s stock closed yesterday at $24.=
38. When DWAC went public, it sold stock for $10 per share, and it has abou=
t $10.20 per share =E2=80=94=C2=A0about $293 million total =E2=80=94=C2=A0i=
n its trust right now. If it shuts down and returns money to shareholders, =
you=E2=80=99ll get $10.20. If it hangs around for another year trying to cl=
ose its deal with TMTG, well, I don=E2=80=99t know what will happen. Maybe =
it will never close the deal and end up paying shareholders back their $10.=
20 a year from now. Maybe it will close the deal and TMTG will be a disaste=
r and the shares will end up being worth $5, or $0. Maybe it will close the=
 deal and TMTG will be a spectacular success and the shares will end up bei=
ng worth $1,000. But the point is that, if DWAC gets this extension and can=
 hang around for another year trying to close the deal, you=E2=80=99ll be a=
ble to sell your DWAC stock on Sept. 9=C2=A0for $24 or so.
  [3]
 If it doesn=E2=80=99t, you=E2=80=99ll just get $10.20. The stock price is =
much higher than the cash-out value, so you should vote to keep it going.
This is not investing advice, but it is pretty obvious, and I doubt anyone =
is going to vote no. Even if you hold DWAC stock for some reason and think =
=E2=80=9CTMTG is a puff of vapor, its real value is=C2=A0zero, I=E2=80=99d =
rather have the cash,=E2=80=9D who cares, you should sell the stock today f=
or $24.38, which is more cash than $10.20.
  [4]
=C2=A0Presumably the=C2=A0buyer=C2=A0would think the real value of TMTG is =
at least $24.38. So everyone who owns DWAC stock at $24.38 should vote yes =
on the extension, and nobody who owns DWAC stock is likely to vote no.
There is, however, a third option, which is not to vote at all. And not vot=
ing is equivalent to  voting against the extension: =E2=80=9CThe affirmativ=
e vote of at least 65% of the Company=E2=80=99s outstanding shares of commo=
n stock =E2=80=A6 will be required to approve the Extension Amendment Propo=
sal.=E2=80=9D About 17.9% of those shares are owned by DWAC=E2=80=99s spons=
or and friends, who will presumably vote yes, but you still need another 47=
.1% (or roughly 57% of the public shareholders) to get to 65%. If DWAC can=
=E2=80=99t get a majority of its shareholders to vote, it will have to cash=
 them out, which they don=E2=80=99t want.
  [5]

So, rationally, they should all vote, and vote yes. But there is no guarant=
ee in life that every single shareholder of the SPAC that is going to buy D=
onald Trump=E2=80=99s social media company=C2=A0is entirely rational. DWAC =
is more or less a meme stock, with a largely retail investor base. And meme=
-stock retail investors,   as we have discussed recently, sometimes don=E2=
=80=99t vote. For instance the SPAC that took Lucid Group Inc. public had t=
o  adjourn its shareholder vote on that deal because it had a lot of retail=
 shareholders and struggled to get them to vote, even though the stock was =
trading in the $20s at the time and shareholders clearly loved the deal. (E=
ventually they=C2=A0approved it.) And that was a merger vote; this is a bor=
ing extension-of-deadline vote, where it might be harder to get enthusiasm.
I have no idea if DWAC will have any trouble getting its vote, but I will s=
ay that its public filings about the vote are a little sweaty. Here=E2=80=
=99s one from this morning, telling shareholders that they should have gott=
en an email with voting instructions and adding, in all caps, =E2=80=9CPLEA=
SE REMEMBER TO CHECK YOUR SPAM FOLDER FOR THE EMAIL.=E2=80=9D And=C2=A0here=
=E2=80=99s=C2=A0one from Tuesday:
Patrick Orlando, CEO of Digital World, stated, =E2=80=9CThis is an importan=
t opportunity for stockholders to have their vote heard and counted. I beli=
eve we have some of the most passionate stockholders of any public company =
and am excited to see how many not only hold DWAC shares but will make the =
effort to vote and have their vote counted. DWAC continues to believe that =
TMTG, our proposed business combination target, holds wonderful potential f=
or our investors. DWAC will have more time to complete a merger if DWAC sto=
ckholders vote =E2=80=9CFOR=E2=80=9D this Extension. We strongly feel the E=
xtension is the right action for our stockholders, to provide more time to =
close a business combination.=E2=80=9D
If you are a meme-stock company then in some important sense you probably d=
o have =E2=80=9Csome of the most passionate stockholders of any public comp=
any,=E2=80=9D but not necessarily=C2=A0in the sense that they vote. And rig=
ht now, DWAC doesn=E2=80=99t need enthusiastic Truth Social posts or wild s=
tock-price rallies. It needs votes.

