      Anti-ESG
   =20
 =20

There are   various substantive theories of environmental, social and gover=
nance investing, theories of what it is supposed to do. Some of those theor=
ies are about maximizing financial returns, while others are about achievin=
g environmental, social and governance goals with your investment dollars.
But there is also just a=C2=A0marketing=C2=A0theory of ESG, which is that i=
nvestors want ESG investments (for some substantive reason or combination o=
f reasons) and are willing to pay higher fees for them. So if you are a big=
 institutional investment manager, you should slap an =E2=80=9CESG=E2=80=9D=
 name on your regular old investment funds, to attract more clients and cha=
rge them more. This seems to be a big business, to the point that regulator=
s and investors   complain=C2=A0a lot about =E2=80=9Cgreenwashing,=E2=80=9D=
 where an investment manager pretends=C2=A0that a regular fund is an ESG fu=
nd for marketing reasons.
But that feels like a three-months-ago sort of issue, and these days =E2=80=
=9CESG=E2=80=9D has become a marketing=C2=A0problem. The US Republican Part=
y has decided that ESG is bad, and is   pushing public pension funds in Rep=
ublican-controlled states to avoid ESG funds. This is tricky for big instit=
utional fund managers, because =E2=80=9CESG=E2=80=9D is probably still=C2=
=A0good marketing too. If you call your fund =E2=80=9CESG,=E2=80=9D that wi=
ll make some people more likely to buy it and other people less likely to b=
uy it, and if you are a giant institutional investor like BlackRock Inc. yo=
u will do a lot of vague balancing to try to appeal to everyone.
But this is also a huge marketing opportunity for=C2=A0other, smaller=C2=A0=
investment managers to try to capture anti-ESG market share from BlackRock =
by leaning into being=C2=A0Not ESG. Like if you just run a regular mutual f=
und, the incentive six months ago was to rebrand it as an ESG fund and say =
=E2=80=9Cooh, we think about climate change, whatever=E2=80=9D to capture E=
SG dollars. Now, if you run a regular mutual fund, there is an incentive to=
 rebrand it as an anti-ESG fund and say =E2=80=9Cwe absolutely never think =
about climate change at all=E2=80=9D to capture state pension money from Re=
publican-controlled states. Or start a new fund company, why not.=C2=A0So:

Enter [Vivek] Ramaswamy, 37, author of the 2021 book Woke, Inc.: Inside Cor=
porate America=E2=80=99s Social Justice Scam. Sensing opportunity, he=E2=80=
=99s started his own investment company with backing from billionaire inves=
tors Peter Thiel and Bill Ackman.
Ramaswamy=E2=80=99s little company, Strive Asset Management LLC, has crazy =
big ambitions. =E2=80=A6 Ramaswamy insists Strive will one day take on Blac=
kRock, a leading proponent of sustainable investing. New York-based BlackRo=
ck manages $8.5 trillion. Strive, located near Columbus, Ohio, manages one =
fund, DRLL, worth about $300 million. The firm has filed to start several m=
ore funds. BlackRock declined to comment. =E2=80=A6
Ramaswamy, too, says his message is nonpartisan and expresses disappointmen=
t that it =E2=80=9Chas been too limited to the American right. It=E2=80=99s=
 not for lack of effort.=E2=80=9D Yet his pitch sounds a lot like a politic=
al manifesto. In language reminiscent of a Donald Trump rally or Fox pundit=
 Tucker Carlson (Ramaswamy has appeared on Carlson=E2=80=99s show), he says=
 Strive will speak for the =E2=80=9Cforgotten,=E2=80=9D the =E2=80=9Cdisemp=
owered,=E2=80=9D the =E2=80=9Cabused=E2=80=9D=E2=80=94for the 100 million-p=
lus ordinary investors whose voices are being drowned out by elitist big mo=
ney.
A Zelig of the conference circuit, he=E2=80=99s cultivating the red-state g=
overnors, treasurers, and pension officials who decide where the public=E2=
=80=99s money flows. =E2=80=9CMoney doesn=E2=80=99t talk, it screams,=E2=80=
=9D Ramaswamy says. =E2=80=9CWe allow people to speak in a way that they ha=
ven=E2=80=99t been able to speak before.=E2=80=9D

You can, and I=E2=80=99m sure=C2=A0Ramaswamy does, have substantive theorie=
s=C2=A0of anti-ESG. Just as with ESG, these theories might be about maximiz=
ing financial returns (=E2=80=9CESG trades returns for wokeness, and I will=
 focus only on returns=E2=80=9D) or about achieving political or other goal=
s (=E2=80=9CESG hurts coal miners and I want to help them=E2=80=9D). But th=
ere is also just an obvious marketing theory of anti-ESG, which is that a b=
unch of huge public pensions are looking for anti-ESG places to put their m=
oney, and if you can meet that demand then that=E2=80=99s a good business.

